    "body": "Thanks Micah. That explanation was very clear. \r\n\r\nJust taking a step back, it seems that there's really a distinction between fungible and non-fungible resources. CPU and bandwidth are non-fungible. It's not feasible to double the CPU load on Monday morning in exchange for halving in on Saturday night. In your analogy they're like road space. \r\n\r\nWhereas state growth *is* fungible across time. The bottleneck is the long-term average, not peak utilization. It is perfectly feasible to let blocks on Monday morning grow state size at two or even ten times the off-peak rate. In the analogy it's more like (real-life) fuel. Cars can and do use more fuel at certain times of day. \r\n\r\nThe limitation of the current EVM gas model is that it doesn't recognize the distinction between fungible and non-fungible resources. Gas refunds are a good thing if they're used to \"pay\" for fungible-heavy operations like SSTORE or CREATE2 or even the transaction base fee. But they're a bad thing if they're used for non-fungible operations like BALANCE, SLOAD or SHA3. \r\n\r\nIf I was designing from scratch, I'd fix it by creating a second type of fungible gas (F-gas). Each OPCODE and fee schedule row would have both a gas and F-gas cost attached. Accounts would be able to \"bank\" F-gas during low cost periods, then use it as a refund to the F-gas specific cost of their transactions. That's a pretty major overhaul though, so I recognize that it's not practical.\r\n\r\nBut a less radical approach might be changing the general-purpose gas refunds to operation specific pre-allocations. For example, maybe let users pre-pay for future SSTORE operations, then \"spend\" those allocations at a much reduced gas fee later.",
